text: From what I see in this trailer, this movie seems to be partially scientifically accurate. It takes place in the same town and for multiple twisters to strike the same place in one day is astronomically rare but not impossible, so technically that part isn't inaccurate. However, for five twisters to be on the ground at once from the same storm and extremely close to each other is impossible. However, two on the ground at the same time is rare but possible since it happened two weeks ago in Nebraska. Also, tornadoes CAN get that big, but again it's rare. The scenes where they are caught in the tornado seem to be pretty accurate though. People, cars, and trucks can get sucked off the ground like toys.
author: vgames89

text: I think it's the events in the past four years that have inspired this movie. The Tuscolusa, Joplin, and Moore tornadoes definitely were an influence. Not to mention the El Reno tornado, while was 2.6 miles wide like the one we see in this trailer; had winds of 300 mph which can pick up an airplane and wipe houses off their foundation; and killed three storm chasers. Also, I'm sure they film the tornado scenes based on first hand encounters.

text: People will complain about the scientific inaccuracy seen in this trailer. Actually, if you look up some of the tornado outbreaks we've had in the past five years you'll find out that it's more accurate than you think. The El Reno tornado was 2.6 miles wide and had winds of around 300 mph. That's more than enough to pick up trucks and airplanes and completely demolish an airport. I'm sure this movie is inspired by events such as the El Reno, Joplin, Moore, and Tuscaloosa tornadoes. Also, sometimes the found footage genre is a bit ridiculous, especially with horror movies. Who would hold the camera the entire time throughout the ordeal lol. But when it comes to storm chaser, their cameras are rolling ALL THE TIME even inside a tornado. So the found footage aspect actually works in this film.

author: Whitney Pyant

text: When I was down storm chasing last spring I asked my chase partner what the difference between and EF4 and an EF5 tornado were, since the official description of both is basically "total devastation."  He said "In an EF4, every single thing is destroyed. There's just, rubble and mud. In an EF5 there is nothing left."  And he was right. We drove through Moore, OK after the EF5 went through and there was just foundation after foundation, scoured clean of every last thing.   I don't understand how reality isn't scary enough for Hollywood. Instead of terror, debris and confusion we get storms in makeup, rendered to look pretty while they rack up kill points as we eat popcorn. We've already got Twister and The Day After Tomorrow and Sharknado for that.  Can't we have even a single tornado movie that takes these things seriously?

text: The way the trailers show the film, it makes it seem like it's a film about them chasing an outbreak of tornadoes. But the way one of the TV spots showed the film, it made it seem like it was basically the world coming to an end in a rather apocalyptic way. The TV spot I'm talking about is the one is showing the MPH speed increasing by 300 MPH.  The film looks awesome, but I'm still confused of the premise. Is the world ending, or is this just a film about chasing a massive tornado?  My original thought of the film was that what appeared to be regular storms began to spiral out of control as the world's weather system begins to literally tear itself apart, eventually resulting in the destruction of society itself.

text: Being a part of the weather community, I do have a concern with this movie. It's mainly that this is how the public will see storm chasing. That might sound like a stupid concern, but look what happened after Twister. And after Storm Chasers. Chasing is NOTHING like you see it in movies and on TV, but many think every chaser gets "stupid" close and that every chaser is out seeking danger, just like on TV. That couldn't be further from the truth. And it concerns me more that there were REAL chaser consultants, who were either completely ignored or stretched the truth more than just a little. You could say I'm biased, which is true, but the object of my concern HAS happened before several times, and it will most likely happen many more.

text: This trailer makes me hurt inside. Don't you see? They're using things that really happened in real disasters where real people died. Take for instance the graduation scene. It was taken from the Joplin 2011 tornado, where the sirens went off at the end of the graduation ceremony, and it was during the ride home that several people were killed. The huge mile wide tornado- also Joplin. During the trailer there were children stuck in a flooding basement. This happened in Moore, Oklahoma, where 7 school children drowned in the basement of their school, where they had been seeking shelter. Lastly, the semi truck trailers being lifted off the ground is based off the events of the Dallas tornado.  Coming from one of these communities, where the disaster that happened not only killed the people we knew and loved, but redefined what life was for every one in the city, (Not to mention destroying at least a third of the city) this really hurts. Why would you ever use the stories of real disasters where PEOPLE DIED in order to make a movie like this? (I know, its cause of the money.....but still!) Yes, this movie might be a thriller/horror movie for some people, but for those of us that come from tornado impacted communities, it's just a reminder of our pain. Even though we've recovered greatly, our pain is still very real. Thanks for taking the time to read, enjoy the movie.

text: Saw the movie and despite some of the unrealistic scenes, it was an insanely intense and quite scary movie. The animations of tornados and other parts of the movie were scary how real they seemed and looked. This is my new favorite movie. I saw Captain Phillips (sorry if i didnt spell it right) and it was really intense and it was a great movie. Then this came along which is probably 3x as intense and this movie has some pretty hilarious parts to it. And last, the movie isn't one of those movies where it takes like a half-hour to get to the good parts. The instant the movie starts, these 4 high-schoolers are in a car and a tornado comes and picks them up and throws them after they tried to film it which obviously lead to their deaths. I would say that this was a great movie and that you should see it.

text: In a disaster film such as this, aren't we supposed to root for the characters to LIVE? I found myself rooting for all of them to die heinously. Yet it didn't happen fast enough. Many disaster films suffer from this, they give you these obnoxious piece of shit characters that you can't possibly root for...and it ruins the film.   Same with films such as "Cloverfield". I WANTED everyone to die, they were atrociously obnoxious. What a fucking waste of money this film was, same as "Cloverfield". Teen angst main characters are very hard to root for. Especially when they're played by 25+ year old pretty boys and boring skanks.   The secret to a good disaster film is to make you root for the main characters to live, to persevere. Today's directors fail to grasp this simple concept.

I think that they did a great job in making this enviroment and tornado destruction, especially the ending one blowing 300 mph, but unfortunately selling point of this movie is basically all it offers. Plot or several plots are generic, characters are bland and really cliche, also not well developed to care. I was laughing when someone died because of how dumb he/she was. It's not believable at all, it is contrived and it tries to be simultaneously comedy and drama, but it just doesn't work. 2/5.
